  "text": "The wild-type Blastocladiella emersonii was a strain continuously subcultured from the original isolate [CITATION_1] . Zoospores were produced by flooding singlegeneration OC (ordinary colourless) plants grown in darkness at 2 4 ' on Difco 'Cantino PYG Agar'. After 15 min. the spore suspension was decanted, passed through filter paper, and used immediately. Population densities were measured by fixing zoospores in 5 % (v/v) glutaraldehyde and counting in a Speirs-Levy Eosinophil chamber. Encystment was studied by putting spore suspensions in 50 ml. Erlenmeyer flasks shaken at 76 oscillations/min. at 2 2 ' in a Warburg bath (Precision Scientific), and either illuminated from below with a built-in incandescent light bank, (3200 ,uW/cm.2 at bottom of flasks) or kept dark with black paint or aluminium foil, Samples were removed at intervals, fixed as above, and scored for percent encystment. The effect of light intensity upon encystment was studied with 50 ml. flasks coated with various thcknesses of silver by the Rochelle Salts method (Hodgman, 1952-3) . Their transmission, ranging from about 3 % to IOO yo, was determined with an incandescent lamp and a Weston electric light meter. The transmission of colour filters (Edmund Scientific) was determined with a Beckman DU spectrophotometer and Gilford attachments.",
